Motivation

  • Weather estimates are based on probabilistic methods for describing uncertainty

  • We use data on past events to extrapolate future events

    • the chance of rain
      • the proportion of prior days with similar atmospheric conditions on which precipitation occurred
    • A 80% chance of rain
      • in 80 out of 100 past cases with similar conditions, precipitation occurred somewhere in the area

  • In this topic, we focus on machine learning methods using probabilities to do classification

    • We first discuss Naive Bayes method
    • then we introduce Linear Discriminant Analysis (and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis)

Introduction to Naive Bayes

General information

  • the 18th-century mathematician Thomas Bayes developed foundational principles
    • describing the probability of events
    • how these probabilities should be revised in light of additional information
  • Classifiers based on Bayesian methods utilize training data to calculate the probability of each outcome based on the evidence provided by feature values

General information

  • When the classifier is later applied to unlabeled data,
    • it uses these calculated probabilities to predict the most likely class for the new example
  • Bayesian classifiers have been used for a variety of tasks, including:
    • Text classification, such as junk email (spam) filtering
    • Intrusion or anomaly detection in computer networks
    • Diagnosing medical conditions given a set of observed symptoms
    • Predicting the likelihood of a customer purchasing a product
    • Predicting whether the Fed is going to raise interest rates

General information

  • Bayesian classifiers are best applied to problems for which the information from numerous attributes should be considered simultaneously to estimate the overall probability of an outcome

  • Many machine learning algorithms ignore features that have weak effects

  • Bayesian methods utilize all available evidence to subtly change the predictions

    • even if a large portion of features have relatively minor effects, their combined impact in a Bayesian model could be quite large

    • the probability of all possible outcomes of a trial must always sum to one
  • A single event cannot happen and not happen simultaneously
    • an event is always mutually exclusive and exhaustive with its complement

Joint probability

  • There could be some non-mutually exclusive events in the same trial

  • If certain events occur concurrently with the event of interest, we may be able to use them to make predictions

Conditional Probability and Bayesâ theorem

  • Independent events

\[P(A\cap B)=P(A)*P(B)\]

  • Conditional probability
    • Given \(P(B)>0\) \[ P(A|B)=\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(B)}\]
  • Bayesâ theorem \[ P(A|B)=\frac{P(A\cap B)}{P(B)}=\frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)}\]

prior probability posterior probability can use frequency table to construct likelihood table

Naive Bayes Method

Introduction

  • a simple method for applying Bayesâ theorem to classification problem

  • Naive Bayes assumes that all of the features in the dataset are equally important and independent

  • in most cases, even when these assumptions are violated, Naive Bayes still performs surprisingly well

  • Due to the algorithmâs versatility and accuracy across many types of conditions, particularly with smaller training datasets, Naive Bayes is often a reasonable baseline candidate for classification learning tasks

Classification with Naive Bayes

An email example

  • The email contains four words: Viagra, money, groceries, and unsubscribe

  • The Naive Bayes learner is trained by constructing a likelihood table for the appearance of these four words (labeled \(W_1\), \(W_2\), \(W_3\), and \(W_4\)) for 100 emails

Classification with Naive Bayes

An email example

  • Using Bayesâ theorem, we can define the problem as shown in the following formula.
    • This computes the probability that a message is spam given that Viagra = Yes, Money = No, Groceries = No, and Unsubscribe = Yes

\[P(spam|W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=Y)=\frac{P(W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=Y|spam)P(spam)}{P(W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=Y)}\]

  1. as additional features are added, tremendous amounts of memory are needed to store the probabilities for all possible intersecting events

  2. many of these potential intersections will never have been observed in past data, which would lead to a joint probability of zero and problems that will become clear later

Classification with Naive Bayes

  • Naive Bayes makes the naive assumption of independence among events
    • assumes class-conditional independence
      • events are independent so long as they are conditioned on the same class value
  • The conditional independence assumption allows us to use the probability rule for independent events
    • This simplifies the numerator by allowing us to multiply the individual conditional probabilities rather than computing a complex conditional joint probability

Classification with Naive Bayes

An email example

  • In our case, it means that

\[P(W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=Y|spam)\] \[=P(W_1=Y|spam)*P(W_2=N|spam)*P(W_3=N|spam)*P(W_4=Y|spam)\]

  • The likelihood table is used to calculate the conditional probabilities of each word given the class value

    • \(P(spam|W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=Y)=?\) (please do the calculation)
    • \(P(spam|W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=N, W_4=N)=?\) (please do the calculation)

Classification with Naive Bayes

  • The Naive Bayes classification method used above can be summarized (or abstracted) by the following setup

  • Let \(K\) be the set of classes, i.e.Â \(k=1, \dots, K\), and \(p\) number of features, i.e.Â \(X_1, \dots, X_p\)

  • The conditional probability of class \(k\) given the features \(x_1, \dots, x_p\) is given by

\[ f_k(x) = P(X=x|Y=k) \quad \text{where} \; x=(x_1, \dots, x_p) \]

  • The naive Bayes assume \(f_k(x)=f_{k1}(x_1) \times f_{k2}(x_2) \times \cdots \times f_{kp}(x_p)\)

  • Under the navie Bayes assumption, the posterior probability of class \(k\) given the features \(x_1, \dots, x_p\) is given by

\[ P(Y=k | X=x) = \frac{P(Y=k) \prod_{j=1}^p f_{kj}(x_j)}{\sum_{l=1}^K P(Y=l) \prod_{j=1}^p f_{lj}(x_j)} \]

  • to estimate the one-dimensional \(f_{kj}\) from \(x_j\), we have a few options:

    • Assume that the \(j\)th predictor is drawn from a univariate normal distribution
      • \(X_j |Y=k ~ N(\mu_{kj}, \sigma^2_{kj})\)
      • this is like QDA except the covariance matrix is diagonal because the predictors are independent
    • Use a non-parametric estimate for \(f_{kj}\)
      • A simple way: Estimate \(f_{kj}(x_j)\) as the fraction of the training observations in the \(k\)th class belonging to a histogram bin
      • Alternatively, use a kernel density estimator, which is essentially a smoothed version of a histogram.
    • For qualitative \(X_j\), simply count the proportion of training observations for the \(j\)th predictor corresponding to each class

The Laplace estimator

  • An example: an email containing âViagra, groceries, money, and unsubscribeâ
    • spam or not?
  • because probabilities in the Naive Bayes formula are multiplied in a chain,
    • this zero-percent value causes the posterior probability of spam to be zero
    • giving the word groceries the ability to effectively nullify and overrule all of the other evidence
  • Even if the email was otherwise overwhelmingly expected to be spam
    • the absence of the word groceries in spam will always veto the other evidence and
    • result in the probability of spam being zero
  • The Laplace estimator adds a small number to each of the counts in the frequency table
    • ensures that each feature has a non-zero probability of occurring with each class
    • Typically, the Laplace estimator is set to one
      • ensures that each class-feature combination is found in the data at least once

The Laplace estimator

  • An illustration
    • Using a Laplace value of 1, we add 1 to each numerator in the likelihood function
    • Please show the new likelihood table (with the Laplace estimator)
  • Exercise:
    • \(P(spam|W_1=Y, W_2=N, W_3=Y, W_4=Y)\)
    • \(P(spam|W_1=N, W_2=Y, W_3=N, W_4=Y)\)
    • compare the results with and without the Laplace estimator for the previous exercise
  • Although the Laplace estimator was added to the numerator and denominator of the likelihoods
    • it was not added to the prior probabilitiesâthe values of 20/100 and 80/100
  • This is because our best estimate of the overall probability of spam and ham remains at 20% and 80% respectively given what was observed in the data

Using numeric features with Naive Bayes

  • Naive Bayes uses frequency tables for learning the data

    • each feature must be categorical in order to create the combinations of class and feature values comprising the matrix

  • discretize numeric features

    • the numbers are put into categories known as bins

Using numeric features with Naive Bayes

  • Reminder: discretizing a numeric feature always results in a reduction of information
  • The choice of the number of bins can have a significant impact on the performance of the model

  • The choice of four bins was based on the natural distribution of data and

    • a hunch about how the proportion of spam might change throughout the day
    • We might expect that spammers operate in the late hours of the night, or
    • they may operate during the day when people are likely to check their email

  • If there are no obvious cut points, one option is to discretize the feature using quantiles

    • this ensures that each bin contains the same number of observations

  • Too few bins can result in important trends being obscured

  • Too many bins can result in small counts in the Naive Bayes frequency table

    • can increase the algorithmâs sensitivity to noisy data

  • The choice of the number of bins is a trade-off between the amount of information retained and the computational complexity of the model

  • The number of bins can be determined by the data or by the user

A Summary of the strengths and weaknesses of Naive Bayes

Strengths Weaknesses
Simple, fast, and very effective Relies on assumption of equally important and independent features
Work well with noisy and missing data with large numbers of features Not ideals for questions with many numeric features
less demanding on the size of training sample Estimated probabilities are less reliable than the predicted classes
easy to obtain the predicted probability

Let us now go to Linear Discriminant Analysis

Introduction to Linear Discriminant Analysis

  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) is a classification method that is based on Bayesâ theorem

  • LDA is a generative model that estimates the probability of each class by modeling the distribution of the features for each class

  • LDA is a linear classifier

    • assumes that the features are normally distributed and
    • that the variance of the features is the same for all classes

  • LDA is a parametric model

    • it estimates the parameters of the normal distributions for each class

  • LDA is a discriminative model

    • it estimates the parameters of the normal distributions for each class

  • some further information about LDA

  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) is a classification method that generalizes Fisherâs linear discriminant

  • LDA is a supervised method that requires labeled data

  • LDA is a generative model that models the distribution of the data in each class

  • LDA is a linear classifier that finds the hyperplane that best separates the classes

  • LDA is a parametric method that assumes that the data is normally distributed

  • LDA is a simple and interpretable method that is widely used in practice

Introduction to Linear Discriminant Analysis

  • The probability of class \(k\) given the features \(X\) is given by

\[ P(Y=k|X)=\frac{\pi_k f_k(X)}{\sum_{l=1}^K \pi_l f_l(X)} \]

\(\quad\) where \(f_k(x)=P(X=x|Y=k)\) is the density function of the features given class \(k\) and \(\pi_k=P(Y=k)\) is the prior probability of Y being class \(k\)

  • For LDA, it uses normal densities for \(f_k(x)\), separately for each class

  • the decision rule is to assign the class with the highest probability

    • classify a new point according to the class with the highest posterior probability
  • When the classes are well-separated
    • the parameter estimates for the logistic regression model are surprisingly unstable
    • Linear discriminant analysis does not suffer from this problem
  • If n is small and the distribution of the predictors X is approximately normal in each of the classes
    • the linear discriminant model is again more stable than the logistic regression model
  • Linear discriminant analysis is popular when we have more than two response classes
    • because it also provides low-dimensional views of the data

Linear Discriminant Analysis

when \(p=1\)

  • the Gaussian densities for each class are given by

\[ f_k(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_k}e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma_k^2}(x-\mu_k)^2} \]

  • the common assumption is that the variance is the same for all classes, \(\sigma_1^2=\sigma_2^2=\cdots=\sigma_K^2\)

  • recall that we define \(p_k(x)=P(Y=k|X=x)\), which can be expressed

\[ p_k(x)=\frac{\pi_k \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu_k)^2}}{\sum\limits_{l=1}^K \pi_l \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma}e^{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu_l)^2}} \]

Linear Discriminant Analysis - Discriminant Functions (\(p=1\))

  • to see which of \(p_k(x)\) is largest, this is equivalent to assigning \(x\) to the class with the largest discriminant score

\[ \delta_k(x)=x\frac{\mu_k}{\sigma^2}-\frac{\mu_k^2}{2\sigma^2}+\log(\pi_k) \]

  • note that the discriminant score is a linear function of \(x\)

  • Execrise:

    • if \(K=2\) and \(\pi_1=\pi_2=0.5\), \(\mu_2=1\), the decision boundary is at \(x=\frac{\mu_1 + \mu_2}{2}\)

Linear Discriminant Analysis

\(p=1\)

  • As usual, we donât know these parameters

  • we can use the training data to estimate the parameters

    • and then plug them into the rule to classify new observations

  • The parameters are estimated by the following formulas

\[ \begin{aligned} \hat{\pi}_k &=\frac{n_k}{n} \\ \hat{\mu}_k &=\frac{1}{n_k}\sum_{i:y_i=k}x_i \\ \hat{\sigma}^2 &=\frac{1}{n-K}\sum_{k=1}^K\sum_{i:y_i=k}(x_i-\hat{\mu}_k)^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{n-K}\sum_{k=1}^K (n_k-1) \hat{\sigma}_k^2 \end{aligned} \]

\(\quad\) where \(\hat{\sigma}^2_k= \frac{1}{n_k -1}\sum_{i: y_i=k}(x_i - \hat{\mu}_k)^2\)

Linear Discriminant Analysis

when \(p>1\)

  • when \(p>1\), the Gaussian densities for each class are given by

\[ f_k(x)=\frac{1}{(2\pi)^{p/2}|\Sigma_k|^{1/2}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(x-\mu_k)^T\Sigma_k^{-1}(x-\mu_k)} \]

\(\quad\) where \(\Sigma_k\) is the covariance matrix for class \(k\) and \(|\Sigma_k|\) is the determinant of \(\Sigma_k\)

  • in LDA, we assume that \(\Sigma_1=\Sigma_2=\cdots=\Sigma_K=\Sigma\)

  • the corresponding discriminant function is given by

\[ \delta_k(x)=x^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k-\frac{1}{2}\mu_k^T\Sigma^{-1}\mu_k+\log(\pi_k) \]

  • note that the discriminant function is a still linear function of \(x\)

Linear Discriminant Analysis

illustration when \(p=2\) and \(K=3\)

  • assume \(\pi_1=\pi_2=\pi_3=\frac{1}{3}\)

  • Bayes decision boundaries are the dashed lines while the LDA decision boundaries are the solid lines

  • Were they known, they would yield the fewest mis-classification errors, among all possible classifiers

  • Ellipses contain 95 % of the probability for each of the three classes

    • The ellipses are centered at the class means, and their shape is determined by the covariance matrix

  • On the right figure, 20 observations were generated from each class, and the corresponding LDA decision boundaries are indicated using solid black lines

Linear Discriminant Analysis

from the discriminant function to the posterior probability

  • after obtaining the estimates \(\hat{\delta}_k(x)\), we cam obtain the posterior probability

\[ \hat{p}_k(x)=\frac{e^{\hat{\delta}_k(x)}}{\sum_{l=1}^K e^{\hat{\delta}_l(x)}} \]

  • hence, classifying to the largest \(\hat{\delta}_k(x)\) is equivalent to classifying to the largest \(\hat{p}_k(x)\)

  • Note that when \(K=2\), we classify to class 1 if \(\hat{p}_1(x)>0.5\) and to class 2 otherwise

  • If we classified to the prior

    • always to class No in this case
    • we would make \(333/10000\) errors, or only \(3.33\%\)

    • Not a big concern here since \(n = 10000\) and \(p = 2\)

Other forms of Discriminant Analysis

  • by altering the forms for \(f_k(x)\), we can obtain different classifiers

  • With Gaussians but different \(\Sigma_k\) in each class, we get Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

  • When \(f_k(x)=\prod^p_{j=1} f_{kj}(x_j)\) in each class, we get Naive Bayes

    • for Gaussian, this is equivalent to LDA with diagonal \(\Sigma\)

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a non-parametric density estimate, we get K-Nearest Neighbors

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a logistic function, we get Logistic Regression

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a tree, we get Classification Trees

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a neural network, we get Neural Networks

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a support vector machine, we get Support Vector Machines

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a random forest, we get Random Forests

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a gradient boosting machine, we get Gradient Boosting Machines

  • When \(f_k(x)\) is a deep learning model, we get Deep Learning

Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA)

  • When the covariance matrices \(\Sigma_k\) are different in each class, the quadratic terms in the discriminant functions will not cancel out

\[ \delta_k(x) = -\frac{1}{2} (x-\mu_k)^T \Sigma_k^{-1} (x-\mu_k) - \frac{1}{2} \log |\Sigma_k| + \log \pi_k \]

Code 
library(tidyverse)
library(MASS)

credit<- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kwan-MSDA/MSDA7003/main/Default.csv")

credit$default <- as.factor(credit$default)

qda_model <- qda(default ~ ., data = credit)
Actual
No Yes
No 9636 239
Yes 31 94
  • \((31 + 239)/10000\)
    • \(2.7\%\) mis-classification rate!
  • why would one prefer LDA to QDA, or vice-versa?
    • The answer lies in the bias-variance trade-off
  • When there are \(p\) predictors, then estimating a covariance matrix requires estimating \(p(p+1)/2\) parameters
    • QDA estimates a separate covariance matrix for each class, for a total of \(Kp(p+1)/2\) parameters
  • With \(50\) predictors this is some multiple of \(1,275\), which is a lot of parameters
    • By instead assuming that the K classes share a common covariance matrix, the LDA model becomes linear in x
    • there are \(Kp\) linear coefficients to estimate
  • LDA is a much less flexible classifier than QDA, and so has substantially lower variance
    • This can potentially lead to improved prediction performance
  • But there is a trade-off:
    • if LDAâs assumption that the K classes share a common covariance matrix is badly off
    • then LDA can suffer from high bias
  • Roughly speaking, LDA tends to be a better bet than QDA if there are relatively few training observations and
    • so reducing variance is crucial

Let us compare with naive Bayes

  • Recall that naive Bayes assumes that the features are conditionally independent given the class

  • Useful when \(p\) is large

    • multivariate methods like QDA (and even LDA) break down
    • the curse of dimensionality
      • the problem of estimating densities in high dimensions
      • the number of parameters grows exponentially with the number of dimensions

  • Gaussian naive Bayes assumes each \(\Sigma_k\) is diagonal

\[\begin{aligned} \delta_k(x) &\propto \log \left [\pi_k\prod_{j=1}^p f_{kj}(x_j) \right ] \\ &=- \frac{1}{2}\sum_{j=1}^p \left [ \frac{(x_j-\mu_{kj})^2}{\sigma^2_{kj}} +\log \sigma^2_{kj} \right ] + \log \pi_k \end{aligned}\]
  • the model can use both continuous and categorical feature vectors
    • for continuous feature, we assume a Gaussian distribution
    • for categorical feature, we assume a multinomial distribution

Logistic Regression vs LDA

  • For a two-class problem, it can be shown that LDA and logistic regression are equivalent

  • for LDA,

\[ \log \frac{P(Y=1|X=x)}{P(Y=0|X=x)} = \beta_0 + \beta^T x=\beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j x_j \]

  • it has the same form as logistic regression

  • the difference is in the estimation of the coefficients

  • logistic regression uses the conditional likelihood based on \(P(Y|X)\)

    • it is known as discriminative learning model
    • it is a direct probability model

  • LDA uses the joint(full) likelihood based on \(P(X,Y)\)

    • it is known as generative learning model

  • in practice, the results are often similar, unless in some special cases

  • when the classes are well-separated

  • when the sample size is small

  • when the number of predictors is large

  • Also, LDA is more robust to outliers

  • logistic regression can alsoquadratic boundaries like QDA

    • by explicitly including quadratic terms in the model

  • Logistic regression is very popular for classification, especially when K = 2

  • LDA is useful when n is small, or

    • the classes are well separated, and
    • Gaussian assumptions are reasonable
    • Also when K > 2

  • Naive Bayes is useful when p is very large
